segments.text: Was Silver Tap celebrated off of the roof of the academic building like it is now?
Was Sully's statue already there when you were a student?
Did you all celebrate Aggie Muster on April 21st?
Oh, I agree.
I think musters, silver taps, midnight yell practice, final review, and commencements, I think, are some of the key events in building Aggie pride.
That's right.
I'm going to do the muster this year in Nashville, Tennessee.
This will be my 25th muster speech.
I'm one of the few people that has ever done the muster speech at College Station that doesn't have an Aggie degree or wasn't a four-star general.
When Final Review was held then, was it held on the place that we call the drill field today?
Did your parents come for graduation and commissioning?
Yes, sir.
And they came on the train.
Do you remember anybody who owned a car when you were a student?
Because I presume no student had a car.
No student had a car.
What was your core outfit's name?
Did y'all have a nickname?
No.
At the time, we got one student in the room.
Remember, I've been back there.
He said, you're pretty sick today.
Yes, sir.
Let's see, was that an infantry outfit?
Did the cavalrymen play polo then?
You weren't involved in any of the athletic teams?
You weren't a member of the...
What were your favorite extracurricular activities?
What did you do for pleasure?
Did you spend much time in the library studying?
Mm-hmm.
And I understand that a freshman could not be harassed while he was in the library studying.
Now, on Saturday nights, where did you and your buddies go to celebrate?
Where you could hide?
Did...
Did you all go to the rock pits, the clay pits?
Were those places to swim then?
Later there would be some gravel pits where they swam.
Did you all do that?
Oh, okay.
Not anymore, but there was then a fish tank?
And what did you wear when you were swimming in the fish tank?
Did you wear anything?
Do you remember going to Houston ever just for fun?
Football game only.
And let's see, did Rice play football yet?
Who was your favorite opponent in football?
Texas?
It still is.
It still is.
I'd rather be in Texas.
All the rest are good to be.
I agree.

But one of the things that I think is good today, that every time Texas achieves something, we want to outdo them, and vice versa, so we are both getting better trying to be better than each other, and the people of Texas gain.
Are you proud to be a Texan?
Yeah, I'm right.
That's right.
I agree with you.
I agree.
How long has your family lived in Texas?
My father was born in Alabama.
Alabama.
Came to Texas 16, 17 years.
He was kind of bigger.
He picked 350 pounds a day.
Oh, that's a lot.
Couldn't pick.
So, he would have come in the 1880s?
Where did he first live in Texas?
West Texas.
And when did your family move to Uvalde?
Oh.
Oh I see.
Ah.
I remember something about that.
First time I've ever heard of a town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
A town club.
So I found out about it.
I went to work with the daily class, but I started to, like, take it out, take it out.
And told me about it.
I don't know.
I didn't tell her I memorized it.
She got that B in that, but I didn't do anything.
I didn't memorize it.
Anyway, she told me what they did.
They were very good.
They didn't tell me what they did.
In those days, did students take Spanish very often?
No.
What about German?
Did you take German in high school?
Because I know during World War I, I have read that we quit teaching German because of the war.
The proper soul.
And I went to the head because I was going to get in.
And I knew it was going to be in the Army.
And I wasn't there very long.
And they say, see, you know, it's a turning point.
Mm-hmm.
Took all of us in.
I see.
I said, T.C., getting ready to go to war.
Right.
Right.
Right.
Right.
Right.
When you would ride the train to and from College Station, you went from College Station to where on the train?
To Houston?
No.
And did you go through San Antonio?
Now, while you were at A&M, was your father ranching or farming?
Farming.
Farming.
And his cash crops were what, cotton?
Onions.
Onions.
What kind of onions then?
White, Bermuda onions?
White, yellow.
How many acres?
I don't remember that.
They gave me an acre.
And that helped to pay your way.
Now, where was he growing onions?
Near what town?
Near Mellon?
Did he own the land or did he rent it?
He owned it?
When had he bought it?
What is that land used for now?
Is that right?
And how many did he grow onions on the same ground year after year?
Since you've been in agriculture, have you ever grown onions?
Because that was tough work, wasn't it?
Onions made more money per acre than cotton?
Oh, yeah, can't beat that.
Can't beat... My... That's a lot of money in that time.
That's a lot.
All right, then, when you got out of A&M, you first went to work for the 4-H...
How did you get that job?
Did you enjoy it?
Did that take you all over the state?
Who were the people that you remember that were helpful?
Tell me what you did in that capacity.
Did you speak or work with the high school teachers?
What was your, do you remember what your pay was in that first job?
$450 a year?
And you lived where?
On the campus at A&M.
For how long did you live there?
Two or three years.
and traveled by train, you were on the road about half the time?
So you learned from missing that train one time.
I never felt right.
Tell me about what the Depression did to people in Texas.
How bad was it?
What did you do during the Depression?
You continued to work.
Did the Depression affect one part of agriculture more than others?
All of it.
So cattle and cotton and everything.
Let's see.
Let me stop this and let you take a rest now, and I'll come back after lunch.
As World War II approached,
What were you doing in the late 30s, early 40s?
You were still with the extension?
Oh.
Carpet, Cremory, Cremory, Plainfield, all the banks, you know.
It'd be the best of the joy that you could find.
I think you're right in the door.
When did you meet Gus Wortham?
How involved in politics were you in the 1930s?
Did you have to go to Austin often to lobby for agriculture?
So you didn't have to work with W. Lee O'Daniel or Jimmy Allred or?
No, I knew them all.
Describe Governor O'Daniel for me then, please.
You say you knew him.
A wheeler dealer?
Was he honest?
I don't know.
And physically, big, small?
Oh, excuse me.
Go ahead.
Chicken, pork, pork, pork, pork, pork, and steak.
Yeah.
I said, can you bring it to anybody?
I said, can you bring it to anybody?
I said, can you bring it to anybody?
Anyway.
Of the agricultural groups during that time, which one had the greatest political influence?
Was it the cattlemen?
And the Farm Bureau?
Which governors cared most about agriculture?
Conley.
Conley?
Now that causes me to ask, of all the governors you know, which governors made the best appointments, appointed the best people to boards and agencies?
Conley.
That's the answer everybody gives.
Good provided.

I've asked how did he select good people, and two or three folks have said he would tell his staff a long time in advance, I need to appoint members to the whatever it is, bring me a list of all the quality people that I ought to consider, and that then from that list he selected high-quality people.
You were mentioning a while ago when you and Governor Daniel chatted before your A&M appointment.
How did your name come to his attention?
Who proposed you or recommended you?
Do you know?
Who?
And do you know how many others he considered when he considered you?
Did he ask you any other questions except co-education questions?
Did you ever work with Gib Gilchrist?
Tell me about him, please, about Mr. Gilchrist.
Did he do a good job at A&M?

His son Henry told me that when they moved there, that he, the son, didn't like it because after living in Austin, College Station seemed so small, but that his father then bribed him by giving him a new bicycle.
He was 13 years old and he said that almost every faculty member and staff member lived on the campus and that he thought it was a long way from College Station to anywhere else.
He also said that College Station was not yet incorporated so that when
Mr. Bryan, up at the First National Bank in Bryan, planned to annex College Station that his father as dean of engineering and some others on the campus got busy and incorporated College Station.
Did any of you former students help with that?
This boy, brother in the back, the father said, Father, give me a little.
I don't know what.
